{"title":"Level 13 — Advanced R Programming","markdown":{"headingText":"Level 13 — Advanced R Programming","headingAttr":{"id":"","classes":["unnumbered"],"keyvalue":[]},"containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-problem}\n**Where this level is headed**\n\nLevel 9 taught you to write functions; Level 10 taught you to automate repeated tasks with loops. This level goes one layer deeper: *how R actually keeps track of variables behind the scenes*, how to build functions that remember state between calls, how to handle errors gracefully instead of letting a script crash, and how to work with the two data types nearly every real dataset eventually needs — text patterns and dates — that this course's mostly-numeric dataset hasn't required yet.\n:::\n\n## What this level covers\n\n- Environments — how R actually stores and looks up variables, and why a function's variables normally disappear once it finishes\n- Closures — functions that \"remember\" values from where they were created, enabling reusable function factories\n- A first look at R's S3 object system, for building your own structured result types\n- Robust error handling with `tryCatch()`, beyond Level 9's `stop()` and `warning()`\n- Debugging tools for finding *why* code fails, not just that it failed\n- Functional programming patterns like `Reduce()` for combining values one at a time\n- Regular expressions for detecting and extracting text patterns\n- General string manipulation beyond what Levels 1-12 have needed\n- Working with dates — parsing, formatting, and calculating differences\n- The basic anatomy of an R package, for turning reusable functions into shareable tools\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-mission}\n**A preview mission**\n\nYour mission across this level: build a small, reusable toolkit — a function factory for flexible threshold checks, a custom result type, and an error-safe file reader — and bring it all together in a capstone that automates reading and validating a folder of clinic files, extending Level 10's automation with real error handling.\n:::\n\n::: {.callout-note}\n## A note on scope\n\nThis level focuses on the R-programming skills that generalize far beyond this course's dataset: environments, closures, error handling, debugging, functional patterns, regex, strings, dates, and package structure. Deeper object-oriented systems (S4, R6) and full package publishing workflows (roxygen2 documentation generation, CRAN submission, Git/GitHub collaboration) are mentioned where relevant but are beyond this course's scope — Level 10's `browser()`-free debugging and this level's S3 introduction give you a solid, practical foundation to build on later.\n:::\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":""},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":"auto","echo":true,"output":true,"warning":false,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":false,"ipynb":null,"enabled":null,"daemon":null,"daemon-restart":false,"debug":false,"ipynb-filters":[],"ipynb-shell-interactivity":null,"plotly-connected":true,"message":false,"engine":"markdown"},"render":{"keep-tex":false,"keep-typ":false,"keep-source":false,"keep-hidden":false,"prefer-html":false,"output-divs":true,"output-ext":"html","fig-align":"default","fig-pos":null,"fig-env":null,"code-fold":false,"code-overflow":"scroll","code-link":true,"code-line-numbers":false,"code-tools":true,"tbl-colwidths":"auto","merge-includes":true,"inline-includes":false,"preserve-yaml":false,"latex-auto-mk":true,"latex-auto-install":true,"latex-clean":true,"latex-min-runs":1,"latex-max-runs":10,"latex-makeindex":"makeindex","latex-makeindex-opts":[],"latex-tlmgr-opts":[],"latex-input-paths":[],"latex-output-dir":null,"link-external-icon":false,"link-external-newwindow":false,"self-contained-math":false,"format-resources":[],"notebook-links":true},"pa